The paper studies the computational complexity of a simplified version of a popular turn-based tactical role-playing game series, which involves analyzing the decision-making process and strategies of the game. This falls under the scope of computational complexity theory (cs.CC) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also involves analyzing the structure of the game map, which can be represented as a graph, and the complexity of graph algorithms (cs.DS, cs.CG). Finally, the paper involves analyzing the complexity of winning conditions, which can be modeled as a game theory problem (cs.GT).
